WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.420
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:07.420 --> 00:00:09.050
Welcome back to Recitation.

00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:11.560
In lecture you've been computing
derivatives of

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:14.000
functions from the limit
definition of derivative.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.940
So today we're going to do
another example of that and do

00:00:16.940 --> 00:00:18.330
some graphing, as well.

00:00:18.330 --> 00:00:20.745
So I've got a problem written
here on the board.

00:00:20.745 --> 00:00:24.470
So we're defining a function f
of x to be 1 over the quantity

00:00:24.470 --> 00:00:26.296
1 plus x squared.

00:00:26.296 --> 00:00:28.600
So what I'd like you to do is
graph the function of the

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:32.110
curve y equals f of x and to
compute the derivative f prime

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:33.960
of x from the definition.

00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:35.790
So why don't you take a couple
of minutes to do that

00:00:35.790 --> 00:00:38.690
yourself, then come back, and
we'll work it out together.

00:00:46.250 --> 00:00:46.660
All right.

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:47.460
Welcome back.

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:52.000
So to start off, let's try
graphing this function f of x.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.750
So one thing you can always do
when you start out graphing a

00:00:54.750 --> 00:00:56.840
function, is to just
plot a few points.

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:59.370
And that'll give you a very
rough sense of where the

00:00:59.370 --> 00:01:02.230
function is, at least
around those points.

00:01:02.230 --> 00:01:05.125
So, for example, when x is
equal to 0 we have f

00:01:05.125 --> 00:01:07.470
of 0 is 1 over 1.

00:01:07.470 --> 00:01:09.300
So that's just 1.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:15.760
So we've got this point
here, 0, 1.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:19.010
And when x is equal to 1, well,
x squared is 1, so the

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:22.910
denominator is 2, so the
function value is 1/2.

00:01:22.910 --> 00:01:25.140
So, all right I'm not going
to draw this to scale.

00:01:25.140 --> 00:01:28.800
I'm going to put x
equals 1 here.

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:38.470
And the function value is 1/2,
so this is the point 1, 1/2.

00:01:38.470 --> 00:01:39.550
And, OK.

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:40.390
We could do one more.

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:44.690
When x is equal to 2,
this function--

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:47.660
2 squared is 4, so that's
5-- so it's 1/5.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:48.310
So I don't know.

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:51.350
1/5 is smaller than
1/2, right?

00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:52.970
So that's maybe--

00:01:52.970 --> 00:01:54.230
down here--

00:01:54.230 --> 00:02:00.210
so this is something like
the point 2, 1/5.

00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:00.520
All right.

00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:04.480
But this is a very rough idea
we're getting, so we can use

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:07.000
some more sophisticated analysis
to get a better idea

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.830
of what this graph is
going to look like.

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:12.910
So the first thing we could
notice, for example, is that

00:02:12.910 --> 00:02:13.997
this is an even function.

00:02:13.997 --> 00:02:14.790
Right?

00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:19.030
If I change the sign of x, if I
replace x by minus x, well,

00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:22.780
x squared and minus x squared
are both equal to x squared.

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:25.070
So if you replace x by
minus x, the function

00:02:25.070 --> 00:02:26.220
value doesn't change.

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:28.570
So this is an even function
that has symmetry

00:02:28.570 --> 00:02:31.850
across the axis here.

00:02:31.850 --> 00:02:33.840
So, you know, for example,
I could just

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:35.280
mirror image these points.

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:38.000
So these points also have to
be on the graph, the points

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.130
minus 1, 1/2 and minus 2, 1/5.

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:44.470
And any other part of the curve
that I draw will be

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:46.130
perfectly mirror imaged.

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:50.020
Another thing to observe is
that x squared is always

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:51.580
greater than or equal to 0.

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:55.260
So 1 plus x squared is
always positive.

00:02:55.260 --> 00:02:59.670
So 1 over 1 plus x squared
is also always positive.

00:02:59.670 --> 00:03:04.340
Also, 1 plus x squared, it
reaches its minimum when x is

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:09.100
equal to 0 and then as x gets
large, either in the positive

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:11.860
direction or in the negative
direction, this gets larger

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:13.590
and larger.

00:03:13.590 --> 00:03:15.610
this, just the 1 plus
x squared part.

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:19.790
So the denominator is getting
larger and larger, while the

00:03:19.790 --> 00:03:21.350
numerator stays constant.

00:03:21.350 --> 00:03:23.940
The whole fraction gets
smaller and smaller.

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:27.410
So as x gets bigger, either
bigger positive or bigger

00:03:27.410 --> 00:03:31.020
negative, the function value
will diminish off to 0, and it

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:33.630
has its maximum value
here at 0.

00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:37.150
Because that's when 1 plus x
squared has its minimum.

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:43.680
So the function sort of has
its maximum here at 0, and

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:46.450
then it flattens out.

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:50.460
And as x gets larger and larger
and larger, this goes

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:54.020
to infinity, so the whole
fraction goes down to 0.

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:55.230
But it never reaches
it, right?

00:03:55.230 --> 00:03:56.700
Because we said it's
always positive.

00:03:56.700 --> 00:04:01.020
And similarly, on
the other side.

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:01.330
OK.

00:04:01.330 --> 00:04:05.840
So that's the graph of
the curve y equals 1

00:04:05.840 --> 00:04:09.250
over 1 plus x squared.

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:10.380
Roughly speaking.

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:11.540
OK.

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:15.320
So now let's talk about
computing the derivative.

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:18.800
So right now, to compute a
derivative, all you have is

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:20.180
the limit definition
of the derivative.

00:04:20.180 --> 00:04:22.530
So when I ask you to compute the
derivative what you've got

00:04:22.530 --> 00:04:27.430
to do is write down what
that definition says.

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:29.610
That's the limit of a
difference quotient.

00:04:29.610 --> 00:04:35.640
So we have, by definition, that
f prime of x is equal

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:39.200
to-- well, it's the limit--

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:44.050
is delta x goes to 0 of some
difference quotient.

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:47.600
So on the bottom of the
difference quotient we just

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:55.740
have delta x, and on the top
we have f of x plus delta x

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:58.340
minus f of x.

00:04:58.340 --> 00:05:01.270
In our case, we have a nice
formula for f of x.

00:05:01.270 --> 00:05:10.026
So this is equal to the limit as
delta x goes to 0 of 1 over

00:05:10.026 --> 00:05:18.920
the quantity 1 plus x plus delta
x quantity squared--

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:22.020
oh, I guess I didn't need
that parenthesis there--

00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:28.600
minus 1 over 1 plus x squared,
and the whole thing

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:30.940
is over delta x.

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:33.610
So, what would be really nice,
of course, is if this were a

00:05:33.610 --> 00:05:36.560
limit where we could just plug
in the value delta x equals 0

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:37.330
and evaluate it.

00:05:37.330 --> 00:05:40.580
But the way the definition of a
derivative works, that never

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:41.290
works, right?

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:43.410
You're always left with
the numerator.

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:47.470
As delta x goes to 0, that top
is always going to be f of x

00:05:47.470 --> 00:05:49.210
minus f of x and it's
going to be 0.

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:52.510
And the bottom is always going
to be delta x going to 0,

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:54.390
which is 0.

00:05:54.390 --> 00:05:55.840
So you always, when you have a
differentiable function, you

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:59.410
always have a derivative that's
going to be a limit of

00:05:59.410 --> 00:06:00.940
a 0 over 0 form.

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:04.514
So you need to do some sort of
manipulation in order to, in

00:06:04.514 --> 00:06:06.960
order to get into a form
you can evaluate it.

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:09.960
What we'd really like is to
manipulate this numerator

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:13.380
somehow and pull out, say,
a factor of delta x.

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:16.190
And then that could cancel with
the delta x we have in

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:17.340
the denominator.

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:18.540
Something, some trick
like that.

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:23.780
Some algebraic or other
manipulation to make this into

00:06:23.780 --> 00:06:26.770
a form where we can plug
in and evaluate.

00:06:26.770 --> 00:06:30.830
So alrright, so right here
there's sort of only one

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:35.660
manipulation that's natural to
do, which is we can add these

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:37.000
two fractions together.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.390
So let's do that, and we
can rewrite this limit.

00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:45.220
The limit is delta
x goes to 0.

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:48.280
All right, I'm going to pull
this 1 over delta x out front

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:51.780
just to make everything look
a little bit nicer.

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:53.590
It's 1 over delta x times--

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:54.480
OK.

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.810
i want to, you know, subtract
these two fractions.

00:06:56.810 --> 00:06:59.080
I want to put them over a common
denominator, so the

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:03.290
denominator is just going
to be the product of the

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:04.010
denominator.

00:07:04.010 --> 00:07:13.760
So that's 1 plus x plus delta
x quantity squared times 1

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:15.780
plus x squared.

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:16.100
OK.

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:19.910
And so this fraction is 1
plus x squared over that

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:21.160
denominator.

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:34.270
And the second one is 1 plus x
plus delta x quantity squared

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:36.520
over that common denominator.

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:36.840
OK.

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:40.260
So we still haven't got where
we want to be yet because we

00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:43.930
still have this 1 over
delta x hanging out.

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:46.320
So OK, so we have to, you
know, keep going.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:49.680
And so here, I guess there's a,
this is sort of a problem

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:53.760
that forces us a little
bit in one direction.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:55.630
You, know, there's not much we
can do with the denominator,

00:07:55.630 --> 00:07:58.410
but here in the numerator we can
expand this out and start

00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:01.470
combining stuff.

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:02.170
So let's do that.

00:08:02.170 --> 00:08:04.190
So this is equal to--

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:06.070
all right, well, the
limit hangs out--

00:08:06.070 --> 00:08:13.840
the limit is delta x goes to
0 of 1 over delta x times--

00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:18.160
OK, so 1 plus x squared
minus--

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:20.780
all right, so if you
expand out x plus

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:22.590
delta x quantity squared--

00:08:22.590 --> 00:08:25.410
using your favorite, either foil
or the binomial theorem

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:27.890
or just whatever you like,
however you like to multiply

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:28.860
two binomials--

00:08:28.860 --> 00:08:38.180
so we get a minus 1 minus x
squared minus 2x times delta x

00:08:38.180 --> 00:08:42.470
minus delta x squared.

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:44.680
That's the top.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:45.820
Ok, and we haven't changed
the bottom.

00:08:45.820 --> 00:08:53.510
It's still 1 plus x plus
delta x squared

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:56.440
times 1 plus x squared.

00:08:59.735 --> 00:09:00.000
OK.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.750
Well, so what?

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:04.300
OK, so now some nice stuff is
starting to happen, which is

00:09:04.300 --> 00:09:07.370
this 1 and this minus 1 are
going to cancel, and this x

00:09:07.370 --> 00:09:09.510
squared and this minus x squared
are going to cancel.

00:09:09.510 --> 00:09:12.300
And then after we cancel those
terms we see that in the

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:15.130
numerator here, everything is
going to have a factor of

00:09:15.130 --> 00:09:15.900
dealt x, right?

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:17.900
These four are going to cancel,
and we'll just be left

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:20.030
with these two terms,
both of which are

00:09:20.030 --> 00:09:21.060
divisible by delta x.

00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:22.750
So that's where this
cancellation we've been

00:09:22.750 --> 00:09:25.330
looking for is going
to come from.

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:27.640
So let's keep going.

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:32.570
So we cancel those, they
subtract, give us 0.

00:09:32.570 --> 00:09:38.380
This limit is equal to the
limit delta x goes to 0.

00:09:38.380 --> 00:09:39.400
OK.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:41.960
And then we can divide this
delta x from the denominator

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:49.000
in, and what we're left with
upstairs is minus 2x minus

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.420
delta x, the whole thing over
the same denominator, still.

00:09:54.420 --> 00:10:04.000
1 plus x plus delta x squared
times 1 plus x squared.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:04.310
All right.

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:04.610
Great.

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:08.660
So we've done this
manipulation.

00:10:08.660 --> 00:10:11.230
We finally found a delta x that
we could cancel with that

00:10:11.230 --> 00:10:13.110
delta x we started with
in the denominator.

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:16.900
And now this limit is
no longer this 0

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:17.960
over 0 form, right?

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:22.090
When delta x goes to 0, the
top goes to minus 2x.

00:10:22.090 --> 00:10:23.000
And the bottom--

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.820
well let's see, this delta x
just goes to 0-- so it's 1

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:28.880
plus x squared times
1 plus x squared.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:30.580
So that's not 0 over 0.

00:10:30.580 --> 00:10:32.370
We can just plug
in to evaluate.

00:10:32.370 --> 00:10:37.385
So this is, just works out
to a minus 2x over--

00:10:37.385 --> 00:10:42.140
OK, 1 plus x squared times 1
plus x squared is 1 plus x

00:10:42.140 --> 00:10:44.480
squared, quantity squared.

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:48.710
And so this is the derivative
that we were looking for.

00:10:48.710 --> 00:10:51.005
This is, just to remind you what
that was, that's d over

00:10:51.005 --> 00:10:57.450
dx of 1 over the quantity
1 plus x squared.

00:10:57.450 --> 00:11:01.780
Now, if you wanted, you could
check this a little bit by

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:04.440
looking at the graph and looking
at this function and

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.630
just making sure that
it makes sense.

00:11:06.630 --> 00:11:11.590
So for example, this function,
this derivative has the

00:11:11.590 --> 00:11:14.480
property that it's
0 when x is 0.

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:16.470
And that's the only
time it's 0.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:18.720
And if we go back and look at
the graph that we drew over

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:21.180
here, we see that's also
a property that

00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:22.500
this graph has, right?

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:26.110
It has this horizontal tangent
line there, and then it

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:31.400
diminishes off to the right and
it, on the left side it

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:35.290
increases, then it has that
horizontal tangent line, and

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:36.940
then it decreases.

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:39.150
And so if we go back to this
function we see, yes indeed,

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:42.880
when x is negative, this whole
thing is positive.

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:46.730
And then at 0 it's 0, and then
it's negative thereafter.

00:11:46.730 --> 00:11:51.180
And similarly, you could note
that this function here is an

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:52.310
odd function.

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:56.450
If you change the sign of x,
that changes the sign of this

00:11:56.450 --> 00:12:00.370
whole expression, and so OK,
and so that makes perfect

00:12:00.370 --> 00:12:01.940
sense back here.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:06.390
The symmetry of this curve is
such that, you know, if we

00:12:06.390 --> 00:12:11.940
look at a tangent line to the
left of 0 and the symmetric

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:15.060
tangent line to the right of
0, they're mirror images of

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:15.570
each other.

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:19.090
So their slopes or exactly
negatives of each other.

00:12:19.090 --> 00:12:22.080
So that's a nice way you can
sort of put the two different

00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:24.010
pieces of this problem together
in order to double

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:25.230
check your work.

00:12:25.230 --> 00:12:27.180
So that's that.